  <h2>The Environment</h2>
  <p>Queensland Government facilities span a wide range of building types and security classifications: courts, government service centres, correctional facilities, departmental offices, regional service buildings and remote community infrastructure. These are not discretionary maintenance environments. Cleaning is a compliance obligation under the QBuild procurement framework, with documented performance obligations, security access requirements, incident reporting standards and audit processes that operate continuously through the life of every contract.</p>

  <h2>The Risk</h2>
  <p>In government cleaning, the risks that end contracts are rarely about cleaning standard. They are compliance failures: credential gaps for personnel accessing security-classified sites, documentation that cannot be produced on demand during an audit, reporting that does not meet government format requirements, or performance records that fall below the contractual threshold during a panel review.</p>
  <p>The QBuild panel framework is designed to identify and remove providers who cannot sustain compliance across these dimensions. It is a continuous test, not a one-time entry requirement.</p>

  <h2>The Scope</h2>
  <p>252 active sites across Queensland. Metropolitan sites in Brisbane and Southeast Queensland. Regional sites across the state. Remote sites in areas where workforce sourcing, materials logistics and emergency response require operational infrastructure that metropolitan-only providers cannot replicate. The portfolio spans primary building services, grounds maintenance, window cleaning, pressure washing and specialist cleaning across all facility types in the Queensland Government estate.</p>

  <h2>What Makes This Complex</h2>
  <ul class="cs-complexity">
    <li>Security site classifications: each facility has its own access requirements; credential management must track individual personnel against site-level requirements, not just hold a general credential register</li>
    <li>Remote and regional logistics: facilities in remote Queensland cannot rely on metropolitan workforce mobilisation or just-in-time materials supply; self-sufficient operational capability is required</li>
    <li>Facility type diversity: courts, service centres, correctional facilities and departmental offices have different cleaning protocols, access conditions and security requirements that must be managed simultaneously within the same management system</li>
    <li>Government audit cycles: the QBuild framework requires performance documentation, incident logs, credential registers and management system evidence to be producible immediately and in government-required formats at any point in the contract period</li>
    <li>Continuous compliance management: ISO 9001, 14001 and 45001 are not one-time certifications; they require internal audit cycles, nonconformance processes and management review that operate continuously across the full 252-site portfolio</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The CPC System</h2>
  <p>CPC's approach to Queensland Government delivery operates on three pillars.</p>
  <p>Certified management systems provide the documented framework under which every site is managed. ISO 9001 for quality processes, ISO 14001 for environmental management and ISO 45001 for work health and safety are not marketing credentials. They are operational systems with internal audit requirements, nonconformance processes and management review cycles. When a government client requests management system evidence, documentation exists because the system operates, not because it was assembled for the request.</p>
  <p>Compliance-controlled workforce management maintains security credential records, manages renewal cycles and ensures access is only granted to personnel whose credentials are current for the specific site classification. This operates as a continuous management function, not a periodic check.</p>
  <p>Government-format reporting produces performance evidence, incident logs, credential registers and attendance documentation in formats that meet Queensland Government accountability requirements. Documentation is captured during normal operations and accessible without a formal request process.</p>

